Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a data set containing 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There were 113,947 loans with 81 variables on each loan documented in the propsper loan dataset. The variables were mostly numeric in nature with some categorical variables. The variables include loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), term, occupation, current loan status, borrower income, and many others. A data dictionary which explains the variable in the dataset can be assessed here.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting a borrower's annual percentage rate (APR).

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect the following features to have either a positive/negative effect on borrower's rating. Stated monthly income, prosper score, credit score, employment status, loan original amount, on time prosper payments, debt to income ratio and recommendations. Among all these, I expect the prosper score and loan original amount to have teh strongest effect.

Correlation Plot: Relationship between pairs were negative or very weak positive. There are no strong positive relationships between any pairs. As expeceted, the relationship betweenBorrowerAPR and ProsperScore and BorrowerAPR and CreditScoreRangeUpperare negative because borrowers with lower score (either Prosper and/or credit) are more likely to pay higher APR. Conversely, higher score means the borrowers are more creditworthy and get lower APR.
A negative relationship was also obeserved between LoanOriginalAmount and BorrowerAPR indicating that as the loan amount increases, APR decreases. It will be interesting to investigate the effect as Term on this relationship as it is possible that BorrowerAPR is lower as bigger LoanOriginalAmount has longer Term for payback. Weak positive correlation was observed between the following pairs - LoanOriginalAmount and ProsperScore; LoanOriginalAmount and CreditScoreRangeUpper; LoanOriginalAmount and StatedMonthlyIncome. This is intuitive as borrowers with more monthly income have better rating and can access higher loans.

A correlation of 0.074 was observed between StatedMonthlyIncome and ProperScore while StatedMonthlyIncome and CreditScoreRangeUpper recorded 0.065. This is expected as people with higher income have higher credit rating.

Surprisingly, home ownership has no effect on ProsperScore; although home owners have higher CreditScoreRangeUpper and LoanOriginalAmount.

In this section, I will create plots of three or more variables to investigate the data even further. The investigations follow from the results of analysis in the bivariate exploration.

This further confirms that proves the point that CreditScoreRangeUpper and LoanOriginalAmount are negatively correlated to BorrowerAPR.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

LoanOriginalAmount and Term has a positive relationship, but the multivariate exploration that included BorrowerAPR neutralised the effect of Term on LoanOriginalAmount. The multivariate exploration of BorrowerAPR, CreditScoreRangeUpper and LoanOriginalAmount confirmed the negative relationship betwen the independent variables and BorrowerAPR.
